\h 2 Shemuel
\toc1 2 Shemuel
\toc2 2 Shemuel
\toc3 2 She.
\mt1 2 Shemuel
\is1 Introduction
\ip \bk Second Shemuel\bk* (commonly, but wrongly known as вҖҳSamuelвҖҷ) is the continuation of \bk First Shemuel\bk*вҖ”the two parts together are considered a single вҖҳbookвҖҷ in the Jewish BibleвҖ”it's only split into two because it was too long to fit on a single scroll.
\ip This the story of David's reign: firstly he ruled what became known as вҖҳYehudahвҖҷ (Judah) in the south east (chapters 1вҖ“4), and eventually, the entire nation, including the much larger area of Yisrael (called вҖҳIsraelвҖҷ in older translations) in the north east (Chapter 5вҖ“24). This document explains how David dealt with his enemies within the country, as well as battling with other nations in order to widen and strengthen his kingdom. David's faith and respect of God is demonstrated here, as well as his love for the people. However, despite that, he was also fierce and he was quite capable of disobeying God to get what he wanted. But God sees everything and seen his prophet Natan (Nathan) with a parable to show David his selfishness. David asked for forgiven for his sin and accepted the punishment that God gave him.
\ip The times of peace and prosperity through the latter parts of David's rule were planted in the minds of the Hebrew people, and in the future when they faced difficulties, they would long for another king like DavidвҖ”a son (better вҖҳa descendantвҖҷ) of David who would love God like him.
\iot Main components of this account
\io1 The kingdom of David in Yehudah \ior 1:1вҖ“4:12\ior*
\io1 The kingdom of David over all Yisrael \ior 5:1вҖ“24:25\ior*
\io2 a. The early years \ior 5:1вҖ“10:19\ior*
\io2 b. David takes Uriyyah's wife \ior 11:1вҖ“12:25\ior*
\io2 c. The battles and the difficulties \ior 12:26вҖ“20:26\ior*
\io2 d. The later years \ior 21:1вҖ“24:25\ior*
\rem This is still a very early look into the unfinished text of the Open English Translation of the Bible. Please double-check the text in advance before using in public.
\ie
\c 1
\s1 David learns about Sha'ul's death
\rem /s1 David Learns of Saul's Death; David Mourns for Saul and Jonathan; David installed as king; David Hears of Saul's Death
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 \add вүҲAfter\add* DavidВҰ141765 returnedВҰ141766 from \add вүҲslaughtering\add* the AmalekitesВҰ141770, he stayed inВҰ141773 TsiklagВҰ141773 for twoВҰ141775 daysВҰ141774. (\add King\add* Sha'ulВҰ141764 \add вүҲwas dead by this timeВҰ141774\add*.)
\v 2 ThenВҰ141777 on the thirdВҰ141780 dayВҰ141779, wow, a manВҰ141782 cameВҰ141796 from Sha'ul's campВҰ141786. He had torn clothesВҰ141789 and dirt on his headВҰ141794, and when he got to DavidВҰ141799 he \add вүҲfell onto his knees and bowedВҰ141802 low\add*.
\v 3 вҖңWhere \add вүҲhave youВҰ141809 come from\add*?вҖқ DavidВҰ141806 \add вүҲasked\add* him.
\p вҖңI \add вүҲwas in Yisrael'sВҰ141813 campВҰ141812, butВҰ141804 managed to escapeВҰ141814\add*.вҖқ he \add вүҲreplied\add*.
\v 4 вҖң\add вүҲWhy? What happened?\add*вҖқ DavidВҰ141818 \add вүҲdemanded\add*. вҖңTell me, pleaseВҰ141825,вҖқ
\p вҖң\add &Our\add* peopleВҰ141841 fled from the battleВҰ141834,вҖқ the man said. вҖңMany fell and died. Even Sha'ulВҰ141844 and his son Yonatan died.вҖқ
\p
\v 5 вҖңHow do youВҰ141857 knowВҰ141857 that Sha'ulВҰ141861 andВҰ141862 Yonatan diedВҰ141860?вҖқ DavidВҰ141850 \add вүҲasked\add* the youngВҰ141853 manВҰ141853 who'd \add вүҲbrought the news\add*.
\p
\v 6 вҖңIВҰ141871 happenedВҰ141870 to be on MtВҰ141872. GilboaВҰ141873,вҖқ the youngВҰ141866 manВҰ141866 \add вүҲreplied\add*, вҖңand listen, Sha'ulВҰ141875 was leaningВҰ141876 on his spearВҰ141879. ThenВҰ141865 wow, the chariotsВҰ141881 and the mastersВҰ141882 of the chariot horsesВҰ141883 overtookВҰ141884 himВҰ141884,\x + \xo 1:6-10: \xt 1Sam 31:1-6; 1Ch 10:1-6.\x*
\v 7 and he turnedВҰ141886 around and sawВҰ141888 me. He calledВҰ141889 me and I \add вүҲanswered\add*, вҖҳHere I am.вҖҷ
\v 8 вҖҳWho are youВҰ141898?вҖҷ he \add вүҲasked\add*. вҖҳI'm an AmalekiteВҰ141902,вҖҷ I told him.
\v 9 ThenВҰ141905 he saidВҰ141905 to me, вҖҳPlease, \add вүҲcome over here\add* andВҰ141905 killВҰ141911 me, because \add вүҲalthough I'm stillВҰ141919 alive, the pain is unbearable\add*.вҖҷ
\v 10 \add вүҲSoВҰ141923\add* I stoodВҰ141923 over him and killedВҰ141925 him, because I knewВҰ141927 thatВҰ141936 \add вүҲwith those wounds\add*, he wouldn't liveВҰ141930. ThenВҰ141923 I tookВҰ141933 the crownВҰ141934 off his headВҰ141939 and the braceletВҰ141940 on his arm, and I broughtВҰ141945 them here to you, my masterВҰ141948.вҖқ
\p
\v 11 ThenВҰ141951 DavidВҰ141952 pulled atВҰ141953 his clothesВҰ141953 \add with his hands\add* and tore them, and all the menВҰ141959 with him \add вүҲdid the same\add*,
\v 12 and theyВҰ141985 mournedВҰ141963 and wept and fastedВҰ141965 untilВҰ141966 the eveningВҰ141968 for Sha'ulВҰ141971 and for his son Yonatan, and for Yahweh's peopleВҰ141978, because \add many\add* \add вүҲIsraelisВҰ141983 had been killed\add*.
\p
\v 13 Then DavidВҰ141990 \add вүҲasked\add* the youngВҰ141993 man \add вүҲwho'd brought the news\add*, вҖңWhere are you from?вҖқ
\p вҖңI'm a foreigner's son,вҖқ he \add вүҲreplied\add*, вҖңan AmalekiteВҰ142004.вҖқ
\v 14 вҖңHow come youВҰ142012 weren't afraidВҰ142012 to \add вүҲkillВҰ142015\add* Yahweh's anointedВҰ142018 \add king\add* \add вүҲwith yourВҰ142014 own hands\add*?вҖқ DavidВҰ142009 \add вүҲasked\add* him.
\v 15 ThenВҰ142021 DavidВҰ142022 calledВҰ142021 to one of \add &his\add* youngВҰ142024 menВҰ142024, вҖңCome \add вүҲover here\add* \add and\add* \add вүҲexecute\add* him.вҖқ \add вүҲSoВҰ142021\add* he struckВҰ142030 him, and he diedВҰ142031.
\v 16 вҖңYour blood'sВҰ142036 on your \add own\add* headВҰ142040,вҖқ DavidВҰ142035 told \add @the Amalekite\add*, вҖңbecause \add вүҲyou admitted in your own words\add* that you, yourself killedВҰ142047 Yahweh's anointedВҰ142050 \add one\add*.вҖқ
\s1 David's song of mourning
\rem /s1 David's Lament for Saul and Jonathan; David's Song for Saul and Jonathan
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 17 Then DavidВҰ142055 sang this funeral song for Sha'ulВҰ142062 and his son Yonatan
\v 18 and saidВҰ142068 \add that it should be\add* taughtВҰ142069 to the \add вүҲpeople\add* of YehudahВҰ142072. \add It's called\add* вҖҳThe bowвҖҷ and indeed, it's writtenВҰ142075 \add down\add* in the Book of Yashar:\x + \xo 1:18: \xt Josh 10:13.\x*
\q1
\v 19 вҖңYisrael'sВҰ142082 splendour \add was\add* slainВҰ142086 \add вүҲin the hills\add*.
\q1 вүҲHow the \add вүҲpowerful\add* \add warriors\add* have \add вүҲdied\add*.
\q1
\v 20 Don't tell \add <them\add* in GatВҰ142094.
\q1 вүҲDon't let \add <them\add* take the news to Ashkelon'sВҰ142099 streetsВҰ142098,
\q1 in case the Philistine \add вүҲwomen\add* celebrate,
\q1 and the daughters of the uncircumcisedВҰ142109 are elated.
\b
\q1
\v 21 \add вүҲYou\add* mountainsВҰ142111 inВҰ142112 GilboaВҰ142112,
\q2 \add may you have\add* no dew or rain \add fall\add* onВҰ142112 you,
\q2 nor fieldsВҰ142120 \add producing grain\add* for offerings.
