\p
\v 23 вҖң\add вүҲNo matter what, I want to\add* run,вҖқ \add he replied\add*.
\p вҖң\add Okay thenВҰ151556,\add* run,вҖқ Yoav told him. \add вүҲSoВҰ151556\add* Ahimaats \add вүҲtook a different route through\add* the Yordan valley andВҰ151556 \add вүҲarrived before\add* the Cushite.
\p
\v 24 \add вүҲNow\add* DavidВҰ151572 was sittingВҰ151573 betweenВҰ151574 the \add вүҲouter and inner\add* gatesВҰ151577. \add вүҲWhenВҰ151572\add* the watchmanВҰ151579 had gone over the gateВҰ151583 roof to the wall, he \add вүҲlooked out\add* and saw, wow, a man was runningВҰ151595 \add towards them\add* aloneВҰ151596.
\v 25 The watchmanВҰ151599 calledВҰ151598 \add down\add* and informed the king, and the king said, вҖңIf he's aloneВҰ151606, \add вүҲhe'll be bringing\add* news.вҖқ
\p \add вүҲAs the runner got closerВҰ151611\add*,
\v 26 the watchmanВҰ151614 looked and saw another man running. \add *He\add* calledВҰ151619 \add down\add* to the gatekeeperВҰ151623 and said, вҖңLook, there'sВҰ151625 \add another\add* man running aloneВҰ151629.вҖқ
\p вҖңHe'll also be bringing news,вҖқ said the kingВҰ151631.
\p
\v 27 вҖңThe \add вүҲgait\add* of the firstВҰ151644 runner is like that of Tsadok'sВҰ151649 son Ahimaats,вҖқ the watchmanВҰ151638 said.
\p вҖңHe's a good man andВҰ151637 he'll be bringing good news,вҖқ said the kingВҰ151651.
\p
\v 28 ThenВҰ151662 Ahimaats calledВҰ151662 \add ahead\add* to the king, вҖңPeace!вҖқ And he \add вүҲknelt down withВҰ151689 his faceВҰ151671\add* to the groundВҰ151672 andВҰ151662 said, вҖңBlessed be YahwehВҰ151689 your godВҰ151677, who's \add вүҲstopped\add* the men who \add вүҲacted\add* againstВҰ151689 my masterВҰ151689 the king.вҖқ
\p
\v 29 вҖңIs the youngВҰ151695 man AbshalomВҰ151696 all right?вҖқ the king \add вүҲasked\add*.
\p вҖңWhenВҰ151692 YoabВҰ151707 sent \add вүҲme\add*, your servant,вҖқ Ahimaats \add вүҲanswered\add*, вҖңI \add вүҲnoticedВҰ151699 a big\add* commotion, butВҰ151692 I don'tВҰ151711 know what \add it was about\add*.вҖқ
\p
\v 30 вҖң\add вүҲGo and standВҰ151718 over there\add*,вҖқ the kingВҰ151716 \add вүҲordered\add*, so he \add вүҲstepped asideВҰ151720\add* and stoodВҰ151721 \add there\add*.
\p
\v 31 ThenВҰ151723, wow, the Cushite \add man\add* arrived andВҰ151723 saidВҰ151726, вҖңMay my masterВҰ151729 the kingВҰ151730 receiveВҰ151728 the good newsВҰ151728, because YahwehВҰ151729 has \add вүҲrescued\add* you today from all thoseВҰ151739 who rose up againstВҰ151740 you.вҖқ
\p
\v 32 вҖңIs the young man AbshalomВҰ151750 all right?вҖқ the king asked \add *him\add*.
\rem /s1 David Mourns for Absalom
\p The \add вүҲman\add* replied, вҖңMay the enemiesВҰ151755 of my masterВҰ151756 the king and all thoseВҰ151759 who rose up againstВҰ151762 you for evil, be like that young man \add is\add*.вҖқ
\p
\v 33 Then the king \add started\add* trembling, and he went up to the room over the gate, and \add started\add* weeping, saying, вҖңOh my son Abshalom, my son. Oh my son Abshalom, I wish I'd died instead of you.вҖқ
\c 19
\s1 Yoav scolds David
\rem /s1 Joab Rebukes the King; Joab Reprimands David
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 \add Soon\add* Yoav was told that the kingВҰ151768 was weeping and mourning over Abshalom'sВҰ151780 \add death\add*,
\v 2 and \add so\add* the victory of that day became mourningВҰ151800 for all the people, because they'd heard that the kingВҰ151798 was grieving for his son.
\v 3 The people \add started\add* \add вүҲquietly heading back into\add* the city, like people \add вүҲwould do when they're ashamed of having to\add* \em flee\em* from a battle.
\v 4 \add вүҲButВҰ151828\add* the king covered his face andВҰ151828 \add kept\add* crying out loudly, вҖңOh my son Abshalom. Oh Abshalom, my son, my son.вҖқ
\p
\v 5 Then Yoav went to the house \add вүҲwhere\add* the king was and said, вҖңToday you've \add вүҲmade your followers feel ashamed\add*вҖ”the ones who saved your life today and the lives of your sons and daughters, and the lives of your wives and your slave-wives.
\v 6 By loving those who hate you and hating those who love you, you'veВҰ151866 \add effectively\add* declared today that your officers and men \add вүҲmean\add* nothing to you. \add It seems to us that\add* if Abshalom was still alive today and we were all dead, then it \add вүҲwould have all been okay to you\add*.
\v 7 \add вүҲSo\add* get up now and go and speak \add вүҲsincerely\add* to yourВҰ151892 servantsВҰ151905, because \add вүҲas Yahweh lives\add*, if you don'tВҰ151902 then you won'tВҰ151902 have a single warrior still withВҰ151922 you by the end of the night, and \add that wouldВҰ151921 result inВҰ151922\add* more trouble for you than \add вүҲanything else that's happened\add* to you since you were \add just\add* a lad.вҖқ
\v 8 \add вүҲSo\add* the king got up and \add went and\add* sat atВҰ151934 the \add city\add* gate , and \add вүҲthe news quickly got around\add* and all the people came to \add вүҲsupport\add* the king.
\s1 David returns to Yerushalem
